{"$schema":"https://json.schemastore.org/sarif-2.1.0.json","version":"2.1.0","runs":[{"tool":{"driver":{"name":"PMD","version":"7.11.0","informationUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/latest/","rules":[{"id":"UseLocaleWithCaseConversions","shortDescription":{"text":"When doing a String.toLowerCase()/toUpperCase() call, use a Locale"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nWhen doing `String::toLowerCase()/toUpperCase()` conversions, use an explicit locale argument to specify the case\ntransformation rules.\n\nUsing `String::toLowerCase()` without arguments implicitly uses `Locale::getDefault()`.\nThe problem is that the default locale depends on the current JVM setup (and usually on the system in which\nit is running). Using the system default may be exactly what you want (e.g. if you are manipulating strings\nyou got through standard input), but it may as well not be the case (e.g. if you are getting the string over\nthe network or a file, and the encoding is well-defined and independent of the environment). In the latter case,\nusing the default locale makes the case transformation brittle, as it may yield unexpected results on a machine\nwhose locale has other case translation rules. For example, in Turkish, the uppercase form of `i` is `İ` (U+0130,\nnot ASCII) and not `I` (U+0049) as in English.\n\nThe rule is intended to *force* developers to think about locales when dealing with strings. By taking a\nconscious decision about the choice of locale at the time of writing, you reduce the risk of surprising\nbehaviour down the line, and communicate your intent to future readers.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#uselocalewithcaseconversions","help":{"text":"\nWhen doing `String::toLowerCase()/toUpperCase()` conversions, use an explicit locale argument to specify the case\ntransformation rules.\n\nUsing `String::toLowerCase()` without arguments implicitly uses `Locale::getDefault()`.\nThe problem is that the default locale depends on the current JVM setup (and usually on the system in which\nit is running). Using the system default may be exactly what you want (e.g. if you are manipulating strings\nyou got through standard input), but it may as well not be the case (e.g. if you are getting the string over\nthe network or a file, and the encoding is well-defined and independent of the environment). In the latter case,\nusing the default locale makes the case transformation brittle, as it may yield unexpected results on a machine\nwhose locale has other case translation rules. For example, in Turkish, the uppercase form of `i` is `İ` (U+0130,\nnot ASCII) and not `I` (U+0049) as in English.\n\nThe rule is intended to *force* developers to think about locales when dealing with strings. By taking a\nconscious decision about the choice of locale at the time of writing, you reduce the risk of surprising\nbehaviour down the line, and communicate your intent to future readers.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Error Prone","priority":3,"tags":["Error Prone"]}},{"id":"EmptyCatchBlock","shortDescription":{"text":"Avoid empty catch blocks"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nEmpty Catch Block finds instances where an exception is caught, but nothing is done.\nIn most circumstances, this swallows an exception which should either be acted on\nor reported.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#emptycatchblock","help":{"text":"\nEmpty Catch Block finds instances where an exception is caught, but nothing is done.\nIn most circumstances, this swallows an exception which should either be acted on\nor reported.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Error Prone","priority":3,"tags":["Error Prone"]}},{"id":"CloseResource","shortDescription":{"text":"Ensure that resources like this InputStream object are closed after use"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nEnsure that resources (like `java.sql.Connection`, `java.sql.Statement`, and `java.sql.ResultSet` objects\nand any subtype of `java.lang.AutoCloseable`) are always closed after use.\nFailing to do so might result in resource leaks.\n\nNote: It suffices to configure the super type, e.g. `java.lang.AutoCloseable`, so that this rule automatically triggers\non any subtype (e.g. `java.io.FileInputStream`). Additionally specifying `java.sql.Connection` helps in detecting\nthe types, if the type resolution / auxclasspath is not correctly setup.\n\nNote: Since PMD 6.16.0 the default value for the property `types` contains `java.lang.AutoCloseable` and detects\nnow cases where the standard `java.io.*Stream` classes are involved. In order to restore the old behaviour,\njust remove \"AutoCloseable\" from the types.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#closeresource","help":{"text":"\nEnsure that resources (like `java.sql.Connection`, `java.sql.Statement`, and `java.sql.ResultSet` objects\nand any subtype of `java.lang.AutoCloseable`) are always closed after use.\nFailing to do so might result in resource leaks.\n\nNote: It suffices to configure the super type, e.g. `java.lang.AutoCloseable`, so that this rule automatically triggers\non any subtype (e.g. `java.io.FileInputStream`). Additionally specifying `java.sql.Connection` helps in detecting\nthe types, if the type resolution / auxclasspath is not correctly setup.\n\nNote: Since PMD 6.16.0 the default value for the property `types` contains `java.lang.AutoCloseable` and detects\nnow cases where the standard `java.io.*Stream` classes are involved. In order to restore the old behaviour,\njust remove \"AutoCloseable\" from the types.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Error Prone","priority":3,"tags":["Error Prone"]}},{"id":"UseArraysAsList","shortDescription":{"text":"Use asList instead of tight loops"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\n\nThe `java.util.Arrays` class has a `asList()` method that should be used when you want to create a new List from\nan array of objects. It is faster than executing a loop to copy all the elements of the array one by one.\n\nNote that the result of `Arrays.asList()` is backed by the specified array,\nchanges in the returned list will result in the array to be modified.\nFor that reason, it is not possible to add new elements to the returned list of `Arrays.asList()`\n(UnsupportedOperationException).\nYou must use `new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList(...))` if that is inconvenient for you (e.g. because of concurrent access).\n\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_performance.html#usearraysaslist","help":{"text":"\n\nThe `java.util.Arrays` class has a `asList()` method that should be used when you want to create a new List from\nan array of objects. It is faster than executing a loop to copy all the elements of the array one by one.\n\nNote that the result of `Arrays.asList()` is backed by the specified array,\nchanges in the returned list will result in the array to be modified.\nFor that reason, it is not possible to add new elements to the returned list of `Arrays.asList()`\n(UnsupportedOperationException).\nYou must use `new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList(...))` if that is inconvenient for you (e.g. because of concurrent access).\n\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Performance","priority":3,"tags":["Performance"]}},{"id":"AssignmentInOperand","shortDescription":{"text":"Avoid assignments in operands"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nAvoid assignments in operands; this can make code more complicated and harder to read.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#assignmentinoperand","help":{"text":"\nAvoid assignments in operands; this can make code more complicated and harder to read.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Error Prone","priority":3,"tags":["Error Prone"]}},{"id":"AvoidInstantiatingObjectsInLoops","shortDescription":{"text":"Avoid instantiating new objects inside loops"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nNew objects created within loops should be checked to see if they can created outside them and reused.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_performance.html#avoidinstantiatingobjectsinloops","help":{"text":"\nNew objects created within loops should be checked to see if they can created outside them and reused.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Performance","priority":3,"tags":["Performance"]}},{"id":"AvoidFileStream","shortDescription":{"text":"Avoid instantiating FileInputStream, FileOutputStream, FileReader, or FileWriter"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nThe FileInputStream and FileOutputStream classes contains a finalizer method which will cause garbage\ncollection pauses.\nSee [JDK-8080225](https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8080225) for details.\n\nThe FileReader and FileWriter constructors instantiate FileInputStream and FileOutputStream,\nagain causing garbage collection issues while finalizer methods are called.\n\n* Use `Files.newInputStream(Paths.get(fileName))` instead of `new FileInputStream(fileName)`.\n* Use `Files.newOutputStream(Paths.get(fileName))` instead of `new FileOutputStream(fileName)`.\n* Use `Files.newBufferedReader(Paths.get(fileName))` instead of `new FileReader(fileName)`.\n* Use `Files.newBufferedWriter(Paths.get(fileName))` instead of `new FileWriter(fileName)`.\n\nPlease note, that the `java.nio` API does not throw a `FileNotFoundException` anymore, instead\nit throws a `NoSuchFileException`. If your code dealt explicitly with a `FileNotFoundException`,\nthen this needs to be adjusted. Both exceptions are subclasses of `IOException`, so catching\nthat one covers both.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_performance.html#avoidfilestream","help":{"text":"\nThe FileInputStream and FileOutputStream classes contains a finalizer method which will cause garbage\ncollection pauses.\nSee [JDK-8080225](https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8080225) for details.\n\nThe FileReader and FileWriter constructors instantiate FileInputStream and FileOutputStream,\nagain causing garbage collection issues while finalizer methods are called.\n\n* Use `Files.newInputStream(Paths.get(fileName))` instead of `new FileInputStream(fileName)`.\n* Use `Files.newOutputStream(Paths.get(fileName))` instead of `new FileOutputStream(fileName)`.\n* Use `Files.newBufferedReader(Paths.get(fileName))` instead of `new FileReader(fileName)`.\n* Use `Files.newBufferedWriter(Paths.get(fileName))` instead of `new FileWriter(fileName)`.\n\nPlease note, that the `java.nio` API does not throw a `FileNotFoundException` anymore, instead\nit throws a `NoSuchFileException`. If your code dealt explicitly with a `FileNotFoundException`,\nthen this needs to be adjusted. Both exceptions are subclasses of `IOException`, so catching\nthat one covers both.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Performance","priority":1,"tags":["Performance"]}},{"id":"UseConcurrentHashMap","shortDescription":{"text":"If you run in Java5 or newer and have concurrent access, you should use the ConcurrentHashMap implementation"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nSince Java5 brought a new implementation of the Map designed for multi-threaded access, you can\nperform efficient map reads without blocking other threads.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_multithreading.html#useconcurrenthashmap","help":{"text":"\nSince Java5 brought a new implementation of the Map designed for multi-threaded access, you can\nperform efficient map reads without blocking other threads.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Multithreading","priority":3,"tags":["Multithreading"]}},{"id":"ReturnEmptyCollectionRatherThanNull","shortDescription":{"text":"Return an empty collection rather than null."},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nFor any method that returns an collection (such as an array, Collection or Map), it is better to return\nan empty one rather than a null reference. This removes the need for null checking all results and avoids\ninadvertent NullPointerExceptions.\n\nSee Effective Java, 3rd Edition, Item 54: Return empty collections or arrays instead of null\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#returnemptycollectionratherthannull","help":{"text":"\nFor any method that returns an collection (such as an array, Collection or Map), it is better to return\nan empty one rather than a null reference. This removes the need for null checking all results and avoids\ninadvertent NullPointerExceptions.\n\nSee Effective Java, 3rd Edition, Item 54: Return empty collections or arrays instead of null\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Error Prone","priority":1,"tags":["Error Prone"]}},{"id":"CloseResource","shortDescription":{"text":"Ensure that resources like this URLClassLoader object are closed after use"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nEnsure that resources (like `java.sql.Connection`, `java.sql.Statement`, and `java.sql.ResultSet` objects\nand any subtype of `java.lang.AutoCloseable`) are always closed after use.\nFailing to do so might result in resource leaks.\n\nNote: It suffices to configure the super type, e.g. `java.lang.AutoCloseable`, so that this rule automatically triggers\non any subtype (e.g. `java.io.FileInputStream`). Additionally specifying `java.sql.Connection` helps in detecting\nthe types, if the type resolution / auxclasspath is not correctly setup.\n\nNote: Since PMD 6.16.0 the default value for the property `types` contains `java.lang.AutoCloseable` and detects\nnow cases where the standard `java.io.*Stream` classes are involved. In order to restore the old behaviour,\njust remove \"AutoCloseable\" from the types.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#closeresource","help":{"text":"\nEnsure that resources (like `java.sql.Connection`, `java.sql.Statement`, and `java.sql.ResultSet` objects\nand any subtype of `java.lang.AutoCloseable`) are always closed after use.\nFailing to do so might result in resource leaks.\n\nNote: It suffices to configure the super type, e.g. `java.lang.AutoCloseable`, so that this rule automatically triggers\non any subtype (e.g. `java.io.FileInputStream`). Additionally specifying `java.sql.Connection` helps in detecting\nthe types, if the type resolution / auxclasspath is not correctly setup.\n\nNote: Since PMD 6.16.0 the default value for the property `types` contains `java.lang.AutoCloseable` and detects\nnow cases where the standard `java.io.*Stream` classes are involved. In order to restore the old behaviour,\njust remove \"AutoCloseable\" from the types.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Error Prone","priority":3,"tags":["Error Prone"]}},{"id":"AvoidLiteralsInIfCondition","shortDescription":{"text":"Avoid using literals in if statements"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nAvoid using hard-coded literals in conditional statements. By declaring them as static variables\nor private members with descriptive names maintainability is enhanced. By default, the literals \"-1\" and \"0\" are ignored.\nMore exceptions can be defined with the property \"ignoreMagicNumbers\".\n\nThe rule doesn't consider deeper expressions by default, but this can be enabled via the property `ignoreExpressions`.\nWith this property set to false, if-conditions like `i == 1 + 5` are reported as well. Note that in that case,\nthe property ignoreMagicNumbers is not taken into account, if there are multiple literals involved in such an expression.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#avoidliteralsinifcondition","help":{"text":"\nAvoid using hard-coded literals in conditional statements. By declaring them as static variables\nor private members with descriptive names maintainability is enhanced. By default, the literals \"-1\" and \"0\" are ignored.\nMore exceptions can be defined with the property \"ignoreMagicNumbers\".\n\nThe rule doesn't consider deeper expressions by default, but this can be enabled via the property `ignoreExpressions`.\nWith this property set to false, if-conditions like `i == 1 + 5` are reported as well. Note that in that case,\nthe property ignoreMagicNumbers is not taken into account, if there are multiple literals involved in such an expression.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Error Prone","priority":3,"tags":["Error Prone"]}},{"id":"AvoidFieldNameMatchingTypeName","shortDescription":{"text":"It is somewhat confusing to have a field name matching the declaring class name"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nIt is somewhat confusing to have a field name matching the declaring type name.\nThis probably means that type and/or field names should be chosen more carefully.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#avoidfieldnamematchingtypename","help":{"text":"\nIt is somewhat confusing to have a field name matching the declaring type name.\nThis probably means that type and/or field names should be chosen more carefully.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Error Prone","priority":3,"tags":["Error Prone"]}},{"id":"ConsecutiveAppendsShouldReuse","shortDescription":{"text":"StringBuffer (or StringBuilder).append is called consecutively without reusing the target variable."},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nConsecutive calls to StringBuffer/StringBuilder .append should be chained, reusing the target object. This can improve the performance\nby producing a smaller bytecode, reducing overhead and improving inlining. A complete analysis can be found [here](https://github.com/pmd/pmd/issues/202#issuecomment-274349067)\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_performance.html#consecutiveappendsshouldreuse","help":{"text":"\nConsecutive calls to StringBuffer/StringBuilder .append should be chained, reusing the target object. This can improve the performance\nby producing a smaller bytecode, reducing overhead and improving inlining. A complete analysis can be found [here](https://github.com/pmd/pmd/issues/202#issuecomment-274349067)\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Performance","priority":3,"tags":["Performance"]}},{"id":"AppendCharacterWithChar","shortDescription":{"text":"Avoid appending characters as strings in StringBuffer.append."},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nAvoid concatenating characters as strings in StringBuffer/StringBuilder.append methods.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_performance.html#appendcharacterwithchar","help":{"text":"\nAvoid concatenating characters as strings in StringBuffer/StringBuilder.append methods.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Performance","priority":3,"tags":["Performance"]}},{"id":"AvoidDuplicateLiterals","shortDescription":{"text":"The String literal \"ISO-8859-1\" appears 5 times in this file; the first occurrence is on line 10"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nCode containing duplicate String literals can usually be improved by declaring the String as a constant field.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#avoidduplicateliterals","help":{"text":"\nCode containing duplicate String literals can usually be improved by declaring the String as a constant field.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Error Prone","priority":3,"tags":["Error Prone"]}},{"id":"InefficientEmptyStringCheck","shortDescription":{"text":"String.trim().length() == 0 / String.trim().isEmpty() is an inefficient way to validate a blank String."},"fullDescription":{"text":"\n\nString.trim().length() == 0 (or String.trim().isEmpty() for the same reason) is an inefficient\nway to check if a String is really blank, as it creates a new String object just to check its size.\nConsider creating a static function that loops through a string, checking Character.isWhitespace()\non each character and returning false if a non-whitespace character is found. A Smarter code to\ncheck for an empty string would be:\n\n```java\nprivate boolean checkTrimEmpty(String str) {\n    for(int i = 0; i < str.length(); i++) {\n        if(!Character.isWhitespace(str.charAt(i))) {\n            return false;\n        }\n    }\n    return true;\n}\n```\n\nYou can refer to Apache's StringUtils#isBlank (in commons-lang),\nSpring's StringUtils#hasText (in the Spring framework) or Google's\nCharMatcher#whitespace (in Guava) for existing implementations (some might\ninclude the check for != null).\n\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_performance.html#inefficientemptystringcheck","help":{"text":"\n\nString.trim().length() == 0 (or String.trim().isEmpty() for the same reason) is an inefficient\nway to check if a String is really blank, as it creates a new String object just to check its size.\nConsider creating a static function that loops through a string, checking Character.isWhitespace()\non each character and returning false if a non-whitespace character is found. A Smarter code to\ncheck for an empty string would be:\n\n```java\nprivate boolean checkTrimEmpty(String str) {\n    for(int i = 0; i < str.length(); i++) {\n        if(!Character.isWhitespace(str.charAt(i))) {\n            return false;\n        }\n    }\n    return true;\n}\n```\n\nYou can refer to Apache's StringUtils#isBlank (in commons-lang),\nSpring's StringUtils#hasText (in the Spring framework) or Google's\nCharMatcher#whitespace (in Guava) for existing implementations (some might\ninclude the check for != null).\n\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Performance","priority":3,"tags":["Performance"]}},{"id":"OverrideBothEqualsAndHashcode","shortDescription":{"text":"Ensure you override both equals() and hashCode()"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nOverride both public boolean Object.equals(Object other), and public int Object.hashCode(), or override neither.  Even if you are inheriting a hashCode() from a parent class, consider implementing hashCode and explicitly delegating to your superclass.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#overridebothequalsandhashcode","help":{"text":"\nOverride both public boolean Object.equals(Object other), and public int Object.hashCode(), or override neither.  Even if you are inheriting a hashCode() from a parent class, consider implementing hashCode and explicitly delegating to your superclass.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Error Prone","priority":3,"tags":["Error Prone"]}},{"id":"CompareObjectsWithEquals","shortDescription":{"text":"Use equals() to compare object references."},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nUse `equals()` to compare object references; avoid comparing them with `==`.\n\nSince comparing objects with named constants is useful in some cases (eg, when\ndefining constants for sentinel values), the rule ignores comparisons against\nfields with all-caps name (eg `this == SENTINEL`), which is a common naming\nconvention for constant fields.\n\nYou may allow some types to be compared by reference by listing the exceptions\nin the `typesThatCompareByReference` property.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#compareobjectswithequals","help":{"text":"\nUse `equals()` to compare object references; avoid comparing them with `==`.\n\nSince comparing objects with named constants is useful in some cases (eg, when\ndefining constants for sentinel values), the rule ignores comparisons against\nfields with all-caps name (eg `this == SENTINEL`), which is a common naming\nconvention for constant fields.\n\nYou may allow some types to be compared by reference by listing the exceptions\nin the `typesThatCompareByReference` property.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Error Prone","priority":3,"tags":["Error Prone"]}},{"id":"DoNotUseThreads","shortDescription":{"text":"To be compliant to J2EE, a webapp should not use any thread."},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nThe J2EE specification explicitly forbids the use of threads. Threads are resources, that should be managed and monitored by the J2EE server.\nIf the application creates threads on its own or uses own custom thread pools, then these threads are not managed, which could lead to resource exhaustion.\nAlso, EJBs might be moved between machines in a cluster and only managed resources can be moved along.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_multithreading.html#donotusethreads","help":{"text":"\nThe J2EE specification explicitly forbids the use of threads. Threads are resources, that should be managed and monitored by the J2EE server.\nIf the application creates threads on its own or uses own custom thread pools, then these threads are not managed, which could lead to resource exhaustion.\nAlso, EJBs might be moved between machines in a cluster and only managed resources can be moved along.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Multithreading","priority":3,"tags":["Multithreading"]}},{"id":"AvoidSynchronizedStatement","shortDescription":{"text":"Use ReentrantLock rather than synchronization"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\n      Synchronization will pin virtual threads and can cause performance problems.\n    "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_multithreading.html#avoidsynchronizedstatement","help":{"text":"\n      Synchronization will pin virtual threads and can cause performance problems.\n    "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Multithreading","priority":3,"tags":["Multithreading"]}},{"id":"NullAssignment","shortDescription":{"text":"Assigning an Object to null is a code smell.  Consider refactoring."},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nAssigning a \"null\" to a variable (outside of its declaration) is usually bad form.  Sometimes, this type\nof assignment is an indication that the programmer doesn't completely understand what is going on in the code.\n\nNOTE: This sort of assignment may used in some cases to dereference objects and encourage garbage collection.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#nullassignment","help":{"text":"\nAssigning a \"null\" to a variable (outside of its declaration) is usually bad form.  Sometimes, this type\nof assignment is an indication that the programmer doesn't completely understand what is going on in the code.\n\nNOTE: This sort of assignment may used in some cases to dereference objects and encourage garbage collection.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Error Prone","priority":3,"tags":["Error Prone"]}},{"id":"AvoidArrayLoops","shortDescription":{"text":"Arrays.copyOf or System.arraycopy are more efficient"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nInstead of manually copying data between two arrays, use the more efficient `Arrays.copyOf`\nor `System.arraycopy` method instead.\n\nTo copy only part of the array, use `Arrays.copyOfRange` or `System.arraycopy`.\n\nIf you want to copy/move elements inside the _same_ array (e.g. shift the elements), use `System.arraycopy`.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_performance.html#avoidarrayloops","help":{"text":"\nInstead of manually copying data between two arrays, use the more efficient `Arrays.copyOf`\nor `System.arraycopy` method instead.\n\nTo copy only part of the array, use `Arrays.copyOfRange` or `System.arraycopy`.\n\nIf you want to copy/move elements inside the _same_ array (e.g. shift the elements), use `System.arraycopy`.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Performance","priority":3,"tags":["Performance"]}},{"id":"RedundantFieldInitializer","shortDescription":{"text":"Avoid using redundant field initializer for 'size'"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nJava will initialize fields with known default values so any explicit initialization of those same defaults\nis redundant and results in a larger class file (approximately three additional bytecode instructions per field).\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_performance.html#redundantfieldinitializer","help":{"text":"\nJava will initialize fields with known default values so any explicit initialization of those same defaults\nis redundant and results in a larger class file (approximately three additional bytecode instructions per field).\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Performance","priority":3,"tags":["Performance"]}},{"id":"CloseResource","shortDescription":{"text":"Ensure that resources like this PrintWriter object are closed after use"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nEnsure that resources (like `java.sql.Connection`, `java.sql.Statement`, and `java.sql.ResultSet` objects\nand any subtype of `java.lang.AutoCloseable`) are always closed after use.\nFailing to do so might result in resource leaks.\n\nNote: It suffices to configure the super type, e.g. `java.lang.AutoCloseable`, so that this rule automatically triggers\non any subtype (e.g. `java.io.FileInputStream`). Additionally specifying `java.sql.Connection` helps in detecting\nthe types, if the type resolution / auxclasspath is not correctly setup.\n\nNote: Since PMD 6.16.0 the default value for the property `types` contains `java.lang.AutoCloseable` and detects\nnow cases where the standard `java.io.*Stream` classes are involved. In order to restore the old behaviour,\njust remove \"AutoCloseable\" from the types.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#closeresource","help":{"text":"\nEnsure that resources (like `java.sql.Connection`, `java.sql.Statement`, and `java.sql.ResultSet` objects\nand any subtype of `java.lang.AutoCloseable`) are always closed after use.\nFailing to do so might result in resource leaks.\n\nNote: It suffices to configure the super type, e.g. `java.lang.AutoCloseable`, so that this rule automatically triggers\non any subtype (e.g. `java.io.FileInputStream`). Additionally specifying `java.sql.Connection` helps in detecting\nthe types, if the type resolution / auxclasspath is not correctly setup.\n\nNote: Since PMD 6.16.0 the default value for the property `types` contains `java.lang.AutoCloseable` and detects\nnow cases where the standard `java.io.*Stream` classes are involved. In order to restore the old behaviour,\njust remove \"AutoCloseable\" from the types.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Error Prone","priority":3,"tags":["Error Prone"]}},{"id":"SimpleDateFormatNeedsLocale","shortDescription":{"text":"When instantiating a SimpleDateFormat object, specify a Locale"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nBe sure to specify a Locale when creating SimpleDateFormat instances to ensure that locale-appropriate\nformatting is used.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_errorprone.html#simpledateformatneedslocale","help":{"text":"\nBe sure to specify a Locale when creating SimpleDateFormat instances to ensure that locale-appropriate\nformatting is used.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Error Prone","priority":3,"tags":["Error Prone"]}},{"id":"UnsynchronizedStaticFormatter","shortDescription":{"text":"Static Formatter objects should be accessed in a synchronized manner"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nInstances of `java.text.Format` are generally not synchronized.\nSun recommends using separate format instances for each thread.\nIf multiple threads must access a static formatter, the formatter must be\nsynchronized on block level.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_multithreading.html#unsynchronizedstaticformatter","help":{"text":"\nInstances of `java.text.Format` are generally not synchronized.\nSun recommends using separate format instances for each thread.\nIf multiple threads must access a static formatter, the formatter must be\nsynchronized on block level.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Multithreading","priority":3,"tags":["Multithreading"]}},{"id":"ConsecutiveLiteralAppends","shortDescription":{"text":"StringBuffer (or StringBuilder).append is called 2 consecutive times with literals. Use a single append with a single combined String."},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nConsecutively calling StringBuffer/StringBuilder.append(...) with literals should be avoided.\nSince the literals are constants, they can already be combined into a single String literal and this String\ncan be appended in a single method call.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_performance.html#consecutiveliteralappends","help":{"text":"\nConsecutively calling StringBuffer/StringBuilder.append(...) with literals should be avoided.\nSince the literals are constants, they can already be combined into a single String literal and this String\ncan be appended in a single method call.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Performance","priority":3,"tags":["Performance"]}},{"id":"RedundantFieldInitializer","shortDescription":{"text":"Avoid using redundant field initializer for 'totalNodes'"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nJava will initialize fields with known default values so any explicit initialization of those same defaults\nis redundant and results in a larger class file (approximately three additional bytecode instructions per field).\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_performance.html#redundantfieldinitializer","help":{"text":"\nJava will initialize fields with known default values so any explicit initialization of those same defaults\nis redundant and results in a larger class file (approximately three additional bytecode instructions per field).\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Performance","priority":3,"tags":["Performance"]}},{"id":"AvoidSynchronizedAtMethodLevel","shortDescription":{"text":"Use block level locking rather than method level synchronization"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nMethod-level synchronization will pin virtual threads and can cause performance problems. Additionally, it can cause\nproblems when new code is added to the method.  Block-level ReentrantLock helps to ensure that only the code that\nneeds mutual exclusion will be locked.\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_multithreading.html#avoidsynchronizedatmethodlevel","help":{"text":"\nMethod-level synchronization will pin virtual threads and can cause performance problems. Additionally, it can cause\nproblems when new code is added to the method.  Block-level ReentrantLock helps to ensure that only the code that\nneeds mutual exclusion will be locked.\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Multithreading","priority":3,"tags":["Multithreading"]}},{"id":"RedundantFieldInitializer","shortDescription":{"text":"Avoid using redundant field initializer for 'lastTag'"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nJava will initialize fields with known default values so any explicit initialization of those same defaults\nis redundant and results in a larger class file (approximately three additional bytecode instructions per field).\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_performance.html#redundantfieldinitializer","help":{"text":"\nJava will initialize fields with known default values so any explicit initialization of those same defaults\nis redundant and results in a larger class file (approximately three additional bytecode instructions per field).\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Performance","priority":3,"tags":["Performance"]}},{"id":"RedundantFieldInitializer","shortDescription":{"text":"Avoid using redundant field initializer for 'pos'"},"fullDescription":{"text":"\nJava will initialize fields with known default values so any explicit initialization of those same defaults\nis redundant and results in a larger class file (approximately three additional bytecode instructions per field).\n        "},"helpUri":"https://docs.pmd-code.org/pmd-doc-7.11.0/pmd_rules_java_performance.html#redundantfieldinitializer","help":{"text":"\nJava will initialize fields with known default values so any explicit initialization of those same defaults\nis redundant and results in a larger class file (approximately three additional bytecode instructions per field).\n        "},"properties":{"ruleset":"Performance","priority":3,"tags":["Performance"]}}]}},"results":[{"ruleId":"UseLocaleWithCaseConversions","ruleIndex":0,"message":{"text":"When doing a String.toLowerCase()/toUpperCase() call, use a Locale"},"locations":[{"physicalLocation":{"artifactLocation":{"uri":"src/main/java/org/6367667f1a6d9265ec01745c/6367667f1a6d9265ec01745c.java"},"region":{"startLine":21,"startColumn":42,"endLine":21,"endColumn":70}}}]},{"ruleId":"EmptyCatchBlock","ruleIndex":1,"message":{"text":"Avoid empty catch blocks"},"locations":[{"physicalLocation":{"artifactLocation":{"uri":"src/main/java/org/6367667f1a6d9265ec01745d/6367667f1a6d9265ec01745d.java"},"region":{"startLine":52,"startColumn":19,"endLine":54,"endColumn":18}}}]},{"ruleId":"CloseResource","ruleIndex":2,"message":{"text":"Ensure that resources like this InputStream object are closed after use"},"locations":[{"physicalLocation":{"artifactLocation":{"uri":"src/main/java/org/636766801a6d9265ec017477/636766801a6d9265ec017477.java"},"region":{"startLine":18,"startColumn":26,"endLine":18,"endColumn":30}}}]},{"ruleId":"UseArraysAsList","ruleIndex":3,"message":{"text":"Use asList instead of tight loops"},"locations":[{"physicalLocation":{"artifactLocation":{"uri":"src/main/java/org/636766801a6d9265ec017477/636766801a6d9265ec017477.java"},"region":{"startLine":19,"startColumn":13,"endLine":19,"endColumn":31}}}]},{"ruleId":"EmptyCatchBlock","ruleIndex":1,"message":{"text":"Avoid empty catch blocks"},"locations":[{"physicalLocation":{"artifactLocation":{"uri":"src/main/java/org/636766801a6d9265ec017477/636766801a6d9265ec017477.java"},"region":{"startLine":34,"startColumn":23,"endLine":36,"endColumn":22}}}]},{"ruleId":"AssignmentInOperand","ruleIndex":4,"message":{"text":"Avoid assignments in operands"},"locations":[{"physicalLocation":{"artifactLocation":{"uri":"src/main/java/org/636766801a6d9265ec017482/636766801a6d9265ec017482.java"},"region":{"startLine":24,"startColumn":16,"endLine":24,"endColumn":68}}}]},{"ruleId":"AvoidInstantiatingObjectsInLoops","ruleIndex":5,"message":{"text":"Avoid instantiating new objects inside loops"},"locations":[{"physicalLocation":{"artifactLocation":{"uri":"src/main/java/org/636766801a6d9265ec017482/636766801a6d9265ec017482.java"},"region":{"startLine":29,"startColumn":36,"endLine":29,"endColumn":63}}}]},{"ruleId":"AvoidFileStream","ruleIndex":6,"message":{"text":"Avoid instantiating FileInputStream, FileOutputStream, FileReader, or FileWriter"},"locations":[{"physicalLocation":{"artifactLocation":{"uri":"src/main/java/org/636766811a6d9265ec017496/636766811a6d9265ec017496.java"},"region":{"startLine":23,"startColumn":24,"endLine":23,"endColumn":39}}}]},{"ruleId":"UseConcurrentHashMap","ruleIndex":7,"message":{"text":"If you run in Java5 or newer and have concurrent access, you should use the ConcurrentHashMap implementation"},"locations":[{"physicalLocation":{"artifactLocation":{"uri":"src/main/java/org/636766821a6d9265ec0174b6/636766821a6d9265ec0174b6.java"},"region":{"startLine":16,"startColumn":40,"endLine":16,"endColumn":68}}}]},{"ruleId":"ReturnEmptyCollectionRatherThanNull","ruleIndex":8,"message":{"text":"Return an empty collection rather than null."},"locations":[{"physicalLocation":{"artifactLocation":{"uri":"src/main/java/org/636766821a6d9265ec0174b6/636766821a6d9265ec0174b6.java"},"region":{"startLine":34,"startColumn":32,"endLine":34,"endColumn":36}}}]},{"ruleId":"ReturnEmptyCollectionRatherThanNull","ruleIndex":8,"message":{"text":"Return an empty collection rather than null."},"locations":[{"physicalLocation":{"artifactLocation":{"uri":"src/main/java/org/636766821a6d9265ec0174b6/636766821a6d9265ec0174b6.java"},"region":{"startLine":37,"startColumn":28,"endLine":37,"endColumn":32}}}]},